title: High resolution measurement of proton resonances in 57Co

x4freetext: High resolution measurement of proton resonances in
57Co

x4freetext: 2-3 microg/cm2 of Fe2O3 powder
was evaporated  onto thin carbon foils (1-5
microg/cm2).
Five silicon surface barrier detectors
were used for the proton measurements, and five
7.6x7.6 cm NaI(Tl) crystals were used to obtain
deexcitation gamma-ray angular distributions.
Excitation functions for elastic and
inelastic scattering of protons on 56Fe were measured
from Ep = 3.1 to 4.0 MeV and five scattering angles:
89, 106, 124, 149, and 160 degrees. The spectra were
stored on magnetic tape for off-line analysis.
Background subtraction for the elastic peaks
consisted of a linear fit to a few channels on each
side of the peak. The elastic and inelastic
scattering data were fit with a multilevel,
multichannel R-matrix code. The program MULTI used to
perform these analyses can simultaneously handle
several hundred resonances of many different spins
and parities, and can include the effects of up to 35
competing channels. In the present work, elastic
scattering and inelastic scattering to the first 2+
state in 56Fe (Ex=0.85 MeV) are assumed to be the
open channels. Shape analysis was sufficient to
determine the orbital momentum of all but the weakest
levels.

x4freetext: In determining the level densities, a correction
was made for weak levels missed experimentally. This
was done by comparing the width distributions with a
Porter-Thomas distribution. The level densities are
expected to have an exponential energy dependence of
the form rho(E,J)~(2J+1)exp[-J(J+1)/2sigma2]exp[E/T],
where T is the nuclear temperature and sigma is the
spin cutoff parameter. Of particular interest here is
the J dependence on level density.
